column6: Dang the 1.1 dropped like a stone.
Gapped down to 0.84 on 29th. The 3M resisting 2% and 10Y isn't going over 3.1%, now 1.91 & 2.88 so should really be 30-70 but will wait a day.
The yield curve is becoming more steep due to rising rate expectations.
yields at the short end are rising but will the Fed really be worried? flat or inverted curves are symptomatic of recessions but not necessarily the direct cause of them.
I expect it to drop around 9 basis points by the time of the next fed. Which is an uncomfortable - as the question is Jun1.

Expectations of the Fed's imminent rate rise should impact the short term interest rate more than the long term, thereby lowering the yield curve. Some useful graphs on this here: https://www.stlouisfed.org/on-the-economy/2017/october/increases-fed-funds-rate-impact-other-interest-rates

The yield spread indicates the likelihood of a recession or recovery one year forward. The spread equals the difference between the short-term borrowing rate set by the Federal Reserve (the Fed) and interest rates on longer term treasury notes, determined by bond market activity.
